  <header class="masthead">
    <p class="wordmark">Work with me</p>
    <p class="by">Lee Wilkers</p>
  </header>

  <p>I&rsquo;ve specialized in being a generalist. That means I don&rsquo;t sell you fancy frameworks or design fads. What I can do, again and again, is help you think clearly about hard institutional problems.</p>

  <p>The useful frames usually come from outside the field where the institution sits (e.g., organizational sociology, decision theory, design research, theories of measurement and scaling, and many others). My job is bringing those frames to your problem.</p>

  <p>I work mostly with teams who are mid-strategy or mid-program when it becomes clear no one has said what the real problem is yet. I&rsquo;m a trained qualitative researcher &mdash; that means a lot of listening carefully, reading carefully, and noticing the gap between what&rsquo;s said and what&rsquo;s happening. Most of my work to date has been in global health and institutional research.</p>

  <hr>

  <p><strong>Where I tend to be useful.</strong></p>

  <ol class="judah-aka-list">
    <li><strong>The brief is not yet the real problem.</strong> What a client asks for at intake is usually a version of the problem that has been approved upward, rehearsed in funding narratives, and tightened enough to sound complete. The version that is actually keeping people up at night tends to surface later &mdash; in the third or fourth conversation, in a sidebar after a long meeting, in a comment that the speaker treats as too obvious to count as a finding. The presented version is rarely wrong, but it is usually partial, and the work cannot move until the version underneath it is sayable in the room.</li>

    <li><strong>Values on the wall are not doing any of the work when an actual decision comes up.</strong> Organizations adopt language like &ldquo;respect,&rdquo; &ldquo;transparency,&rdquo; &ldquo;country ownership,&rdquo; and that language gets onto onboarding decks, mission statements, and donor narratives without ever being given an operating definition that two staff members would agree on. When a real decision arrives &mdash; a partnership pulled, a hire made, a country office cut &mdash; the listed values stay outside the room, and the decision proceeds on other grounds entirely. The values are still decorative; they are no longer load-bearing. Nobody needs them to choose.</li>

    <li><strong>The dashboard improves while the encounter, the outcome, or the relationship gets worse.</strong> Each line item on a campaign dashboard &mdash; coverage, reach, integration, satisfaction &mdash; was originally meant to track something real: an encounter at a door, a clinical outcome at follow-up, a relationship with a community over multiple rounds. Over time, the line item drifts away from what it was supposed to indicate, and improving the number becomes easier than improving the thing the number was about. Saying so out loud sounds, to most stakeholders, like an attack on measurement itself, which makes the metric easier to defend than to fix.</li>

    <li><strong>The consultation was structured to confirm the decision, not to inform it.</strong> Stakeholder input is solicited, logged, and synthesized; recommendations are produced; a deliberation document is filed. But the decision-makers had already converged on a direction before the consultation began, and what the process generated was permission to proceed rather than a genuine engagement with what was heard. The alternative pattern is similar in outcome but different in mechanism &mdash; the decision sat unmade long enough that the calendar ran out, and the silence itself became the policy. Both look like consultation from the outside until the moment a decision arrives.</li>

    <li><strong>Programs run on practices that never made it into the protocol.</strong> In most of the work I do, what gets logged to the donor and what gets delivered at the household door are two different programs, and the gap between them is rarely accidental. Distributors develop informal sequencing &mdash; a second pass on the south end of the route, a quiet renegotiation with a household head, a verbal consent script that the written form does not anticipate &mdash; and these adjustments are what make the round work. The supervisor checklist captures the version that can be audited, not the version that was delivered. Seeing what is actually happening means watching the route, not reading the form.</li>

    <li><strong>The reasoning that produced the current setup left when the people did.</strong> Programs accumulate decisions over many rounds, and each decision usually made sense in its moment &mdash; a routing change after a stockout, a supervisor ratio set after a quality complaint, a consent script revised after a particular community refusal. But when staff turnover or a leadership transition happens, the reasoning behind those decisions tends to leave with the people who made them, even when the decisions themselves stay in the SOP. The next team rebuilds the same answer from scratch, or rebuilds a worse one, because the path that produced the existing setup is no longer legible to anyone in the room.</li>

    <li><strong>Capacity built over years can be dissolved in a single budget cycle.</strong> Years of expertise live in particular people doing particular work &mdash; the staffer who knows which community will refuse a written consent form and why, the partner who has spent four rounds learning a route&rsquo;s quirks, the team lead who can read which complaint is field-real and which is administrative noise. A line-item cut or a strategic-priority shift can clear that capacity from the org chart faster than it can be rebuilt, and once it is gone, the next funding cycle pays substantially more to reconstruct it badly. The budget conversation is rarely framed as a conversation about what gets lost, but that is the conversation it is.</li>
  </ol>

  <hr>

  <p><strong>Getting started.</strong> If you&rsquo;d like to work together, send me a short or long note about the problem you&rsquo;re working on. I&rsquo;ll ask a few follow-up questions to figure out whether I can be useful before either of us puts time or money down. The more context you share, the better I can prepare. I usually reply within a few days; first calls typically happen within a week or two.</p>

  <p>If you&rsquo;d like to read more before our first call, <a href="/consider-the-tree/">Consider the tree</a> is the longer written version of how I work.</p>

  <hr>

  <p><strong>Working with me.</strong> Most engagements start with a paid thought-sparring conversation: <strong>$350 for a 60&ndash;90 minute call</strong>. I send a few prep questions a day or two ahead. The call is where I work out whether I can be useful to your problem, and where you work out whether you want to keep going.</p>

  <p>Within a few days after the call, you get a short written follow-up: what I would actually do, what I would want to know more about, and whether I think I am a fit. If we keep going, we agree scope and rate in writing &mdash; usually a fixed-fee deliverable or an hourly block, your preference.</p>

  <p>If $350 is too much, write anyway. Rate flexes for early-stage or public-interest work. I usually have capacity for one or two new engagements at a time.</p>

  <hr>

  <p><strong>Deliverables.</strong> Not every engagement ends in a deliverable. When there is one, it usually takes one of these shapes:</p>

  <ul class="judah-bullets">
    <li>Synthesis memos (5&ndash;15 pages) on a question your team can&rsquo;t get clean on &mdash; <em>Do we have evidence of impact, or not? Did the donor actually sign off on that scope change, or did we assume? Was this CQI or a study?</em> &mdash; usually after several meetings that haven&rsquo;t converged.</li>
    <li>Program audits. What&rsquo;s working, what&rsquo;s reported as working, where the two diverge. Confidential.</li>
    <li>Problem-framing memos for grant proposals, before the drafting starts. Most proposals that fail in writing failed in framing two weeks earlier.</li>
    <li>Workshop facilitation when a team has been circling the same disagreement across multiple meetings.</li>
    <li>Draft text. Policy, IRB, protocol, manuscript framing, board memos. I produce the first draft; you take it from there.</li>
  </ul>

